# PawPal+ — Class Diagram

UML class diagram based on the objects, attributes, and methods brainstormed in
[reflection.md](../reflection.md) (Step 2 — Building Blocks).

```mermaid
classDiagram
    class Owner {
        +int owner_id
        +str name
        +int available_minutes
        +dict preferences
        +add_pet(pet) void
        +set_preferences(preferences) void
        +set_available_time(minutes) void
    }

    class Pet {
        +int pet_id
        +int owner_id
        +str name
        +str species
        +str breed
        +list~Task~ tasks
        +add_task(task) void
        +edit_task(task_id, ...) void
        +remove_task(task_id) void
        +list_tasks() list~Task~
    }

    class Task {
        +int task_id
        +int pet_id
        +str name
        +str category
        +int duration
        +str priority
        +str preferred_time
        +str recurrence
        +bool completed
        +edit(...) void
        +mark_done() void
        +is_recurring() bool
    }

    class Scheduler {
        +date date
        +dict constraints
        +list~Task~ tasks
        +sort_tasks() list~Task~
        +filter_tasks() list~Task~
        +resolve_conflicts() void
        +generate_plan() Schedule
        +explain() str
    }

    class Schedule {
        +date date
        +list entries
        +str reasoning
        +add_entry(time, task) void
        +total_time() int
        +display() void
    }

    Owner "1" --> "*" Pet : owns
    Pet "1" --> "*" Task : has
    Scheduler ..> Task : reads
    Scheduler ..> Owner : reads constraints
    Scheduler ..> Schedule : creates
    Schedule "1" o-- "*" Task : contains
```

## Relationships

- **Owner → Pet** (one-to-many): an owner owns one or more pets.
- **Pet → Task** (one-to-many): each pet has many care tasks.
- **Scheduler → Task / Owner** (dependency): the scheduler reads a pet's tasks and the
  owner's constraints as inputs.
- **Scheduler → Schedule** (dependency): the scheduler produces a `Schedule`.
- **Schedule ◇→ Task** (aggregation): a schedule contains references to the tasks it slotted
  into the day.
